# Communication Style

## Audience

The user is a senior product designer who runs UDS and works almost
entirely through cloud agents. Write to that person — not to a developer
peer.

**Senior designer means they understand technical concepts.** They are
not asking to be talked down to. They're asking you not to hide behind
jargon when plain language works just as well, and not to bury the
answer under implementation detail they didn't ask for.

When in doubt, picture handing the reply to a senior designer at a
product company who reads pull requests and changelogs every day but
doesn't write the code themselves. That's the audience.

## Default chat tone

- **Lead with the answer.** First sentence = the conclusion or the
  outcome. Reasoning, options, and caveats come after, and only if they
  add value.
- **Use jargon when it's the clearest word, not by default.** A
  technical term is fine — sometimes it's the most precise option and
  swapping it out makes the answer longer, vaguer, or wrong. Use it
  then. Don't use it to sound thorough.
  - If you can express the same idea in plain language without losing
    accuracy or making the sentence longer, do that.
  - If the user is going to act on the exact name — copy it, search
    for it, paste it into another tool, debug a token regression with
    it — use the exact name.
- **Be concise.** Short paragraphs. Short bullet lists. No preamble,
  no recap of the user's question, no "great question" energy.
- **Don't narrate tool calls.** Don't say "let me read the file" or
  "I'll run the script now." Just do it. Summarize at the end.
- **Don't restate the obvious.** If a step succeeded, one line is
  enough. Don't paste raw output unless it matters.
- **Match the user's register.** If they're asking a debugging
  question with specific function names and file paths, mirror that.
  If they're asking what something does or what changed, summarize at
  the designer level and offer to "show the technical detail" if they
  want more.

## Designer voice vs technical voice

The left column is the default for chat replies. The right column is
fine in the chat body **when the user is debugging, asked for the
implementation, or needs the exact name**. The wrong move is defaulting
to the right column when the left column was clearer.

| Designer voice (default) | Technical voice (when the specifics matter) |
|---|---|
| "I added a new Button size." | "I added an `xs` value to the Button `size` prop." |
| "The chip now darkens on hover." | "The chip's `:hover` state now binds the `surface-interactive-hover` token." |
| "I added an entry to the docs-site changelog." | "Appended a `SITE_CHANGELOG` entry to `data/site-changelog.ts`." |
| "Draft components on the orange page in Figma are skipped by sync." | "Pages whose names contain `{Cursor}{Ignore}` are filtered out by `uds-figma-preflight.mdc`." |
| "Two themes have a contrast warning on the primary action." | "AnyoneHome and Inhabit fail WCAG AA on `surface-interactive-default` — 3.77:1 and 3.19:1 vs the 4.5:1 threshold." |
| "I couldn't find this in Figma — want me to check the components file?" | "`figmaNodeId` is null in this component's spec — should I run `link-figma-nodes`?" |
| "Saved — ready for you to review." | "Committed `8d3a1f` to `cursor/...` and pushed; PR #38 updated." |

When you've genuinely moved into a technical conversation (the user is
debugging, you're walking through how something works, the answer
hinges on an exact name), the right column is appropriate. Otherwise,
default to the left.

## Voice extends to human-facing docs prose

The same designer voice applies to **prose written into the docs site
for human readers**. This is in addition to chat replies, not instead
of them.

That covers:

- **Rendered page copy** in `uds-docs/app/(site)/**` — page ledes,
  section headers, callouts, descriptions, FAQ entries.
- **Prose fields in `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json`** —
  `description`, `whenToUse`, `whenNotToUse`, and the strings inside
  `dosDonts.dos[]` / `dosDonts.donts[]`. These render verbatim into
  the Guidelines tab. They're machine-loaded but human-read.
- **Prose strings in `accessibility`** — `keyboard[].action`,
  `screenReader[].announcement`, `wcag[].howMet`. These are read by
  humans planning component work.
- **`uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/impl.json` `description`** — the
  one-line summary at the top of the Implementation Reference panel.
- **`uds-docs/uds/CHANGELOG.globalNotes.json`** — hand-curated
  non-component release notes. The version key is metadata; the prose
  is for readers.
- **`uds-docs/data/site-changelog.ts` `SITE_CHANGELOG` entries** —
  the typed fields (`version`, `date`, `type`) are structured metadata,
  but the `text` is prose that renders directly on the live Changelog
  page. Designer voice. Per-component `changelog.json` is different —
  it stays technical voice (audits depend on it). See
  [`uds-site-changelog.mdc`](./uds-site-changelog.mdc) §"Voice and
  length" for the full contract.
- **`uds-docs/README.md` and `uds-docs/AGENTS.md` narrative sections**
  — same audience, same voice.

**Not in scope: anything under `.cursor/`** (rules, skills, agents).
Those are agent-consumed instructions — see the technical-voice table
below.

Same rules apply: lead with the answer, plain language, technical
terms when they're the clearest word. Don't write "canonical
ratification of the proposed pattern" when "a pattern we still need to
agree on" says the same thing.

**Important caveat: this rule does not authorize autonomous rewrites
of `uds-docs/uds/` content.** The Figma source-of-truth rule
(`uds-source-of-truth.mdc`) still applies. If you notice
designer-voice drift in a `spec.json` description and the user did not
ask you to fix it, surface the finding — don't rewrite it. When the
user does authorize a spec edit (or a Figma round-trip lands one),
this voice is the standard.

## Where technical voice is non-negotiable

These artifacts MUST keep their technical detail. Do not "simplify"
them — downstream tooling, audits, schemas, and the engineering layer
all depend on the exact vocabulary.

| Artifact | Why technical detail is required |
|---|---|
| **Code itself** (HTML, CSS, JS, shell scripts) | Use the vocabulary the codebase already uses. Code is for runtime, not for reading comfort. |
| **Code comments** | Only there to explain WHY or non-obvious intent. When they exist, they're precise — name the constraint, the trade-off, the bug they're working around. |
| **`.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, `.cursor/skills/*/SKILL.md`, `.cursor/agents/*.md`** | Agent-consumed instructions. The agent needs the exact file paths, schema field names, script names, and command flags to execute. Use the vocabulary the agent will encounter at runtime. Plain-language rationale wrapping is fine, but the operational detail must stay precise. |
| **JSON schemas** (`uds-docs/uds/schemas/*.json`) | Full schema vocabulary, no creative paraphrasing. Editors validate against these. |
| **Per-component `changelog.json` `entries[]`** | Each entry references real tokens, props, file paths, states. `audit-changelog-currency.sh` and the aggregator depend on this. SITE_CHANGELOG is different — it's prose that renders on the live page and uses designer voice. See [`uds-release-workflow.mdc`](./uds-release-workflow.mdc). |
| **Structured spec fields** (`props[]`, `events[]`, `slots[]`, `states[]`, `accessibility.wcag[]`, `accessibility.contrast[]`, `acceptanceCriteria[]`) | Typed contracts. Component-page render code reads them by shape. Don't paraphrase prop names or event names. |
| **`impl.json` `tokens[]` and `html`** | Token names are exact (`--uds-color-...`). Example HTML uses the actual class names. The Code-tab Implementation Reference depends on both. |
| **Audit and diagnostic output** | Figma findings follow `Confidence / Risk / Reason / Default action` per [`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`](./uds-figma-change-classification.mdc). Token, contrast, completeness, inspector, and CI audit reports keep their structured terminology. |
| **Git commit messages and PR descriptions** | Dev-to-dev (and dev-to-future-you). Name files, scripts, audits, version numbers, what changed and why. Mirror the technical voice the codebase uses. |
| **Figma write summaries** | The `File / Page / Node / Operation / Old value / New value / Rollback note` shape from [`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc) is fixed. |

## How to decide which voice to use

If you're not sure:

1. **Is a human reading this prose for understanding?** → designer voice
2. **Is a machine parsing it, or is a downstream audit/aggregator
   depending on its shape?** → technical voice
3. **Is it code?** → use what the codebase uses
4. **Is it a comment?** → explain WHY, precisely
5. **Is it a chat reply where the user is debugging or asked for
   implementation?** → technical voice is fine in the chat body, just
   don't over-do it
6. **Is it a chat reply where the user is checking in or asking what
   happened?** → designer voice, with an offer to show the detail

When still in doubt, default to less technical and offer to expand.

## Relation to other rules

- This rule does not override
  [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc),
  [`uds-site-changelog.mdc`](./uds-site-changelog.mdc),
  [`uds-release-workflow.mdc`](./uds-release-workflow.mdc),
  [`uds-source-of-truth.mdc`](./uds-source-of-truth.mdc),
  [`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`](./uds-figma-change-classification.mdc),
  or any other content-shape rule. Those rules describe what artifacts
  must say. This rule describes how the prose and chat replies sound
  — and which artifacts get prose treatment vs technical treatment.
- Companion personal-rule text lives in **Cursor Settings → Rules →
  User Rules** so this voice follows the user's account into other
  projects and cloud agent sessions. The User Rule and this workspace
  rule must stay in sync; if you update one, update the other.
